AGI - France has raised to the maximum level of alert of the Vigipirate anti-terrorism plan after the attack in Moscow claimed by Isis. "In the face of the claim of the attack by the Islamic State and the threats that weigh on our country, we decided to bring the position of Vigipirate to its highest level: emergency attack," said Prime Minister Gabriel Attal at the end of the defense council held at the Eliseo. In January the Vigipirate plan had been declassified at level 2 ("strength security - risk of attack"). &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Vigipirate is the name of the French national security plan that aims to prevent and protect against terrorist threats. The term "Vigipirate" is an acronym for "Vigilance et Protection des Installations Contre les Risques d'Attentats Terroristes à l'ègard de la Nation" (Vigilance and Protection of Installations against the Risks of Terroristic Attacks in Nation Comparisons) and was established in France in 1978. It has undergone several revisions over the years to adapt to changing terrorist threats and provides for a series of security measures at national, regional and local level, which can be implemented in response to emergency situations or terrorist threats.
&nbsp;
The measures envisaged by the Vigipirate plan include increasing the presence of security forces in sensitive public places such as airports, railway stations, schools, government buildings and places of worship, as well as more stringent security controls and greater vigilance on suspicious activities.
&nbsp;
The Vigipirate plan is divided into several levels of threat, ranging from the "vigilance" level (vigilance) to the "urgence attack" level (a bombing emergency), depending on the severity of the terrorist threat and the risk of public security. The activation of the different levels depends on the evaluations of the national and local security authorities.

