AGI - In force the new Hong Kong National Security Act, just four days after its unanimous approval by the Legislative Council in the midst of increasing international criticism for its possible impact on freedom and autonomy of citizens.
&nbsp;
The head of the executive, John Lee>, signed the law on Friday claiming to carry out "a historical mission in accordance with the trust placed by the Chinese central authorities". Lee pointed out that this new regulation plays a crucial role in providing a safe and stable environment for business and companies and that, "without this legal framework, these could face financial losses, be subject to sabotage or even suffer attacks".
&nbsp;
Article 23 establishes a series of offences that may lead to a maximum sentence of life impairment, including treason, insurrection, impairment of a member of the Chinese armed forces and collusion with external forces to harm or weaken public infrastructure in order to jeopardize the nation.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The reform has created an intense debate and has been the subject of fierce criticism by democratic governments > and Western organizations, which foresee the beginning of a "new era of authoritarianism" that could put into crisis the principle "a country, two systems" which was fundamental for the autonomy and special statute of the city.
&nbsp;
"The reason why the law was passed so quickly and unanimously is the criticism of Chinese President Xi Jinping > to the executive for being unable to promulgate it before," explained to the Efe the synagogue of the Chinese study center of Usanas, Frank Lehberger. According to the expert, from now on "any individual representing a mortal threat to the survival of the communist regime has the potential to become a target, especially the inhabitants of Hong Kong, who enjoyed individual freedom legally guaranteed and who have never existed in China".
&nbsp;
Lehberger warned that "with this powerful tool the semiautonomous city starts to become a place characterized by uncertainty, suspicion, intimidation, complaints and fear of being imprisoned without a fair trial in court, which will cast a dark shadow on any professional or commercial interaction. &nbsp;
